```
library(tidyverse)
library(modelr)

#plot data in sim2
ggplot(sim2) + geom_point(aes(x, y))

#fit model and generate predictions
sim2_mod <- lm(y~x, data = sim2)

grid <- sim2 %>% data_grid(x)

grid <- grid %>% add_predictions(sim2_mod)

#visualize predictions
ggplot(sim2, aes(x)) + 
  geom_point(aes(y = y)) + 
  geom_point(data = grid, aes(y = pred), color = "purple", size = 3)

#categorical and quantitative

#plot sim3
ggplot(sim3, aes(x1, y)) + geom_point(aes(color = x2))

#two possible models
m1 <- lm(y~x1 + x2, data = sim3)

m2 <- lm(y~x1*x2, data = sim3)

#grid and predict
grid <- sim3 %>% data_grid(x1, x2) %>% gather_predictions(m1, m2)

#facet
ggplot(sim3, aes(x1, y, color = x2)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_line(data = grid, aes(y = pred)) + 
  facet_wrap(~model)

#graph residuals
sim3 <- sim3 %>% gather_residuals(m1, m2)

ggplot(sim3, aes(x1, resid, color = x2)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  facet_grid(model ~ x2)
```

--It was the actor who wept while presenting the scene from the play, not Hamlet. Hamlet was upset with himself for not having taken action yet. If the actor had such emotion from a fictional play, Hamlet chastises himself for not acting on something in real life.
--I don't see how you get from the "miraculous organ" to Claudius' eyes.
--Yes, Claudius' 'confession' may not be from speaking but from reacting. That's a powerful claim.
--So, don't panic on this early assignment. Do be careful that your claims are accurate so you can get full power in your writing.
